[[File:Niwata Jinja Torii.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Niwata Shrine''' (にわたじんじゃ) is a shrine in {{ill|lt=Shisō|Q877216|WD=Q877216|1=Shisō, Hyōgo}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|WD=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN|lt=small Shikinaisha}}, and its former {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=old shrine rank|1=UNKNOWN}} was village shrine.

=== History ===
=== Founding ===
According to shrine tradition, its beginning was the construction of a sacred sanctuary following divine revelation on {{ill|lt=February 11|Q2335|WD=Q2335|1=February 11}}, year 14 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Seimu|Q316672|WD=Q316672|1=Emperor Seimu}} ({{ill|lt=131|Q31740|WD=Q31740|1=AD 131}}), and it is said that the honden and other buildings were later built in the time of {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}}.

According to the '{{ill|lt=Harima no Kuni Fudoki|Q11498726|WD=Q11498726|1=Harima no Kuni Fudoki}}', after Iwa Ōkami ({{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}) completed final negotiations in the land of Iwa, he gathered the deities who had joined in achieving the great work of nation-building, brewed sake, selected a pure court of mountains and rivers, and held a banquet of consolation. This shrine is said to be that pure court where the banquet was held. It also records that when dried rice carried as emergency food was rehydrated, part of it molded and produced alcohol components, leading to the discovery of sake.

=== Historical outline ===
In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=register of deities|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, completed in year 5 of {{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Enchō|1=Enchō}} ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}), "Niwata Shrine" is listed in {{ill|lt=Shisō District|Q7499122|WD=Q7499122|1=Shisō District, Hyōgo}} of {{ill|lt=Harima Province|Q1047523|WD=Q1047523|1=Harima Province}}, and ranked as a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN|lt=small Shikinaisha}}.

The shrine buildings were repaired in year 11 of {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} ({{ill|lt=1671|Q7610|WD=Q7610|1=1671}}), but burned down in November of year 3 of {{ill|lt=Bunkyū|Q730266|WD=Q730266|1=Bunkyū}} ({{ill|lt=1863|Q7701|WD=Q7701|1=1863}}), and were rebuilt in year 4 of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} ({{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|WD=Q7746|1=1871}}). In February of Meiji 7 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

